# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# USAGE NOTES
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# SYNTAX:
# pattern @username @org/team-name
#
# PATTERNS:
# - Use * for wildcards
# - Use ** for recursive directory matching
# - Use / at the end to match directories only
# - Patterns are case-sensitive
#
# BEST PRACTICES:
# 1. Start with broad default ownership, then add specific rules
# 2. Use team mentions (@org/team) instead of individuals for scalability
# 3. Balance thoroughness with review burden - too many owners slow development
# 4. Document why certain files have specific ownership requirements
# 5. Review and update this file quarterly as team structure evolves
# 6. Test changes by creating a draft PR to see who gets auto-assigned
#
# BRANCH PROTECTION:
# To enforce code owner approval:
# 1. Go to Settings → Branches → Branch protection rules
# 2. Add rule for main/master branch
# 3. Enable "Require review from Code Owners"
#
# TROUBLESHOOTING:
# - If code owners aren't being assigned, check GitHub username/team spelling
# - Ensure teams have repository access (Settings → Collaborators & teams)
# - Verify the CODEOWNERS file is in the root, docs/, or .github/ directory
# - Check GitHub Actions logs for CODEOWNERS syntax errors
#
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# END OF CODE OWNERS CONFIGURATION
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
